<pretext>
    <article xml:id="notes">
        <worksheet xml:id="sec-8-2">
        <title><m>\S 8.2</m>: Derivative Rules</title>



				<exercise>
                    <title>Problems</title>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            If <m>f</m> is differentiable at <m>x</m> and <m>c \in \mathbb{R}</m>, prove that the function <m>cf</m> is also has a derivative at <m>x</m> and <m>(cf)'(x) = cf'(x)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            If <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are differentiable at <m>x</m>, show that the function <m>f+g</m> is also has a derivative at <m>x</m> and <m>(f+g)'(x) = f'(x) + g'(x)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Suppose <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are differentiable at <m>x</m>.
Prove each of the following:
<ol>
  <li>
    <p>
      (Product Rule) The function <m>fg</m> is differentiable at <m>x</m>.
      Moreover, its derivative function is given by
      <md>
        (fg)'(x) = f'(x)g(x) + f(x)g'(x).
      </md>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      (Quotient Rule) The function <m>f/g</m> is differentiable at <m>x</m> provided <m>g(x) \neq 0</m>.
      Moreover, its derivative function is given by
      <md>
        \left(\frac{f}{g}\right)'(x) = \frac{f'(x)g(x) - f(x)g'(x)}{[g(x)]^{2}}.
      </md>
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                              Define <m>g: \mathbb{R}\to \mathbb{R}</m> via
<md>
  g(x) = \begin{cases}0, &#x26; \text{if } x \in \mathbb{Q} \\ 1, &#x26; \text{otherwise.}\end{cases}
</md>
Now, define <m>f: \mathbb{R}\to \mathbb{R}</m> via <m>f(x) = x^{2}g(x)</m>.
Determine where <m>f</m> is differentiable.
                            </p> 
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                
                    
                </exercise>

                
                

        </worksheet>
    </article>
</pretext>